1. Initial Design Limitations
The original structure was a simple task tracker with basic automation (start/completion timestamps).
We realized that the formula-based approach for calculating task durations was prone to rounding issues, especially when tasks were completed quickly.
The initial task age metric (days only) didn't provide enough granularity for short tasks.
2. Formula and Formatting Pitfalls
Using mixed date and time formats caused discrepancies in task duration calculations.
We initially rounded cycle time to whole minutes, which hid short task durations and caused confusion.
We also realized that separating operational data (like raw task inputs) from calculated KPIs would simplify the structure.
3. Refactoring Decisions
After testing, we decided to separate raw task data from calculated metrics, making future dashboard building easier.
We adopted a more structured layering approach: raw input sheet, automation script, and a separate analysis dashboard sheet.
This refactor will ensure easier future maintenance and better scalability.
4. Automation Challenges
The Apps Script onEdit trigger worked, but it required careful column mapping to avoid misfires.
We had to standardize status values (e.g., “Completed” vs “Complete”) to prevent script errors.
In future iterations, we’ll implement error handling to ensure timestamps aren’t overwritten if a user edits the status multiple times.
5. Next Steps
Document the new architecture in a dedicated file.
Begin building the GitHub repo with version history.
Plan the next refactor to integrate with a dashboard and future automation.
